        <div class="col-md-8 offset-md-2">
            <h2>About the Kelly Criterion</h2>
            <p class="lead">Understanding the mathematical foundation of optimal portfolio allocation</p>

            <div class="card mb-4">
                <div class="card-body">
                    <h3>What is the Kelly Criterion?</h3>
                    <p>The Kelly Criterion is a mathematical formula that determines the optimal size of a series of bets to maximize long-term growth. In portfolio management, it helps determine the optimal allocation of capital across different investments.</p>
                    
                    <h4>The Formula</h4>
                    <p>The basic Kelly formula for a single investment is:</p>
                    <div class="formula">
                        f* = (μ - r) / σ²
                    </div>
                    <p>Where:</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>f* is the Kelly fraction (optimal allocation)</li>
                        <li>μ is the expected return</li>
                        <li>r is the risk-free rate</li>
                        <li>σ² is the variance (volatility squared)</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="card mb-4">
                <div class="card-body">
                    <h3>Risk Management</h3>
                    <p>While the Kelly Criterion provides the mathematically optimal allocation for maximum growth, it can be too aggressive for most investors. Common risk management approaches include:</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Half Kelly:</strong> Using 50% of the Kelly fraction</li>
                        <li><strong>Quarter Kelly:</strong> Using 25% of the Kelly fraction</li>
                        <li><strong>Eighth Kelly:</strong> Using 12.5% of the Kelly fraction</li>
                    </ul>
                    <p>These fractional Kelly strategies reduce the expected growth rate but significantly reduce the risk of ruin.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="card">
                <div class="card-body">
                    <h3>Important Considerations</h3>
                    <ul>
                        <li>The Kelly Criterion assumes you know the true probabilities and returns</li>
                        <li>It's sensitive to estimation errors in expected returns</li>
                        <li>Transaction costs and taxes are not considered</li>
                        <li>It assumes you can reinvest all profits</li>
                    </ul>
                    <p>Therefore, the Kelly Criterion should be used as one of many tools in portfolio management, not as the sole decision maker.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>

